{
  "answer": "Step 1: The formula for the effective rate of protection ($v_j$) is given as:\\\\\\\\n$$ v_j \\equiv \\frac{t_j - \\sum_i \\theta_{ij} t_i}{1 - \\sum_i \\theta_{ij}} $$\\nStep 2: Economic intuition behind the components of the formula:\\\\\\\\n- $t_j$: This represents the tariff on the final good $j$. It reflects the direct impact of the tariff on the price of the final product in the domestic market.\\\\\\\\n- $t_i$: This represents the tariff on intermediate inputs $i$ used in the production of good $j$. Tariffs on intermediate goods increase the cost of production, reducing the effective protection provided by the tariff on the final good.\\\\\\\\n- $\\theta_{ij}$: These are the distributive shares of intermediate input $i$ in the production of final good $j$. They quantify the proportion of input $i$ used in the production process of $j$, thus determining how much the tariff on $i$ affects $j$.\\\\\\\\n- Numerator ($t_j - \\sum_i \\theta_{ij} t_i$): This part calculates the net tariff effect after accounting for the influence of tariffs on intermediate inputs. It adjusts the nominal tariff on the final good by subtracting the weighted average tariff effect of intermediate inputs.\\\\\\\\n- Denominator ($1 - \\sum_i \\theta_{ij}$): This normalizes the net tariff effect by considering the total share of intermediate inputs in the production of good $j$. It ensures that the effective protection rate reflects the overall impact on the final product's price relative to its production costs.\\\\\\\\nIn summary, the formula captures the net effect of tariffs on both final and intermediate goods, providing insight into how trade policies influence resource allocation and sectoral outputs."
