{
  "answer": "To prove that $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is a countable dense subset of $\\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$ using the definition of separability:\\nStep 1: Show that $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is countable.\\\\\\n- Recall that $\\mathbb{Q}$, the set of rational numbers, is countable. Since $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is the Cartesian product of $\\ell$ copies of $\\mathbb{Q}$, it follows that $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is also countable because the Cartesian product of finitely many countable sets is countable.\\\\\\nStep 2: Show that $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is dense in $\\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$.\\\\\\n- Let $x = (x_1, x_2, ..., x_{\\ell}) \\in \\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$ and $\\epsilon > 0$. By the density of $\\mathbb{Q}$ in $\\mathbb{R}$, for each coordinate $x_i$, there exists a rational number $q_i \\in \\mathbb{Q}$ such that $|x_i - q_i| < \\frac{\\epsilon}{\\sqrt{\\ell}}$. Define $q = (q_1, q_2, ..., q_{\\ell}) \\in \\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$. Then, the Euclidean distance between $x$ and $q$ satisfies:\\\\\\n$$ d(x, q) = \\sqrt{(x_1 - q_1)^2 + (x_2 - q_2)^2 + ... + (x_{\\ell} - q_{\\ell})^2} < \\sqrt{\\ell \\cdot \\left(\\frac{\\epsilon}{\\sqrt{\\ell}}\\right)^2} = \\epsilon $$\\\\\\nThus, for every $x \\in \\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$ and $\\epsilon > 0$, there exists $q \\in \\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ such that $d(x, q) < \\epsilon$. Therefore, $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is dense in $\\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$.\\\\\\\\nConclusion: Since $\\mathbb{Q}^{\\ell}$ is both countable and dense in $\\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$, it follows that $\\mathbb{R}^{\\ell}$ is separable."
}

