{
  "answer": "Step 1: Symmetry of the Prokhorov metric.\\\\\\nTo prove symmetry, we need to show that $\\rho(P, Q) = \\rho(Q, P)$. From Lemma 9.3.7, $\\rho(P, Q) = \\inf\\{\\epsilon > 0 : \\forall F \\text{ closed}, P(F) \\leq Q(F^\\epsilon) + \\epsilon\\}$. Similarly, $\\rho(Q, P) = \\inf\\{\\epsilon > 0 : \\forall F \\text{ closed}, Q(F) \\leq P(F^\\epsilon) + \\epsilon\\}$. Since the roles of $P$ and $Q$ are interchangeable in these definitions, it follows directly that $\\rho(P, Q) = \\rho(Q, P)$. Thus, the Prokhorov metric is symmetric.\\\\\\\\nStep 2: Triangle inequality of the Prokhorov metric.\\\\\\\\nTo prove the triangle inequality, we need to show that $\\rho(P, R) \\leq \\rho(P, Q) + \\rho(Q, R)$. Let $\\epsilon_1 = \\rho(P, Q)$ and $\\epsilon_2 = \\rho(Q, R)$. By definition, for every closed set $F$, $P(F) \\leq Q(F^{\\epsilon_1}) + \\epsilon_1$ and $Q(F) \\leq R(F^{\\epsilon_2}) + \\epsilon_2$. Combining these inequalities, we get $P(F) \\leq R((F^{\\epsilon_1})^{\\epsilon_2}) + \\epsilon_1 + \\epsilon_2$. Using the property of sets $(F^{\\epsilon_1})^{\\epsilon_2} \\subseteq F^{\\epsilon_1 + \\epsilon_2}$, we conclude that $P(F) \\leq R(F^{\\epsilon_1 + \\epsilon_2}) + \\epsilon_1 + \\epsilon_2$. Therefore, $\\rho(P, R) \\leq \\epsilon_1 + \\epsilon_2 = \\rho(P, Q) + \\rho(Q, R)$. This proves the triangle inequality."
}

