{
  "answer": "To prove Lemma 2.8.19, we proceed as follows:\\nStep 1: Let $ u $ be a supermodular function, i.e., $ \\\\[u(x \\vee y) + u(x \\wedge y) \\geq u(x) + u(y)\\\\] $ holds for all $ x, y \\in X $.\\nStep 2: Define a monotonic increasing transformation $ g: \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R} $. By definition, $ g $ satisfies $ g(a) \\leq g(b) $ whenever $ a \\leq b $.\\nStep 3: Consider the transformed function $ v(x) = g(u(x)) $. We aim to show that $ v(x) $ is quasi-supermodular, i.e., $ [v(x) > v(x \\land y)] \\Rightarrow [v(x \\lor y) > v(y)] $.\\nStep 4: Assume $ v(x) > v(x \\land y) $. This implies $ g(u(x)) > g(u(x \\land y)) $.\\nStep 5: Since $ g $ is monotonic increasing, $ u(x) > u(x \\land y) $ must hold.\\nStep 6: From the supermodularity of $ u $, we know $ u(x \\lor y) + u(x \\land y) \\geq u(x) + u(y) $.\\nStep 7: Rearranging gives $ u(x \\lor y) - u(y) \\geq u(x) - u(x \\land y) $.\\nStep 8: Since $ u(x) > u(x \\land y) $, it follows that $ u(x \\lor y) > u(y) $.\\nStep 9: Applying the monotonicity of $ g $ again, $ v(x \\lor y) = g(u(x \\lor y)) > g(u(y)) = v(y) $.\\nConclusion: Therefore, $ v(x) $ satisfies the condition for quasi-supermodularity, completing the proof."
}

