  "answer": "To show that the class E = {(-∞, r] : r ∈ ℝ} generates the Borel σ-field B on ℝ, we proceed as follows:\\nStep 1: Recall that the Borel σ-field B on ℝ is defined as the smallest σ-field containing all open subsets of ℝ.\\nStep 2: Observe that the class E consists of half-open intervals of the form (-∞, r], where r is any real number. These intervals are not open but are fundamental building blocks for constructing open sets.\\nStep 3: Note that any open interval (a, b) in ℝ can be expressed as a countable union of intervals from E. Specifically, (a, b) = ⋃_{q ∈ ℚ ∩ (a,b)} (-∞, q], where ℚ denotes the set of rational numbers.\\nStep 4: Since the Borel σ-field B is closed under countable unions, it follows that all open intervals (a, b) belong to the σ-field generated by E.\\nStep 5: Because the Borel σ-field B is the smallest σ-field containing all open intervals, and since the σ-field generated by E contains all open intervals, it follows that the σ-field generated by E is at least as large as B.\\nStep 6: Conversely, since E ⊆ B, the σ-field generated by E cannot exceed B.\\nConclusion: Therefore, the class E generates the Borel σ-field B on ℝ."
}

