{
  "answer": "Step 1: Define the Net Advantage to Leasing (NAL) formula under different tax rates.\\nThe NAL formula under different tax rates is derived as follows:\\\\\\nNAL = PV(Lessee Tax Shield) - PV(Lessor Tax Shield) + PV(Salvage Value) - PV(Purchase Price)\", where:\\\\n- PV(Lessee Tax Shield): Present value of the tax shield enjoyed by the lessee due to interest deductions on lease payments. This is calculated as the lease payment multiplied by the lessee's marginal tax rate.\\\\n- PV(Lessor Tax Shield): Present value of the tax shield enjoyed by the lessor due to depreciation deductions on the leased asset. This is calculated as the depreciation amount multiplied by the lessor's marginal tax rate.\\\\n- PV(Salvage Value): Present value of the salvage value of the asset at the end of the lease term.\\\\n- PV(Purchase Price): Present value of the cost of purchasing the asset outright.\\\\\\nStep 2: Explain each component of the formula.\\\\n1. PV(Lessee Tax Shield): The lessee benefits from a tax deduction on the lease payments made, reducing their taxable income. This tax shield is calculated as the lease payment multiplied by the lessee's marginal tax rate.\\\\n2. PV(Lessor Tax Shield): The lessor benefits from a tax deduction on the depreciation of the leased asset, reducing their taxable income. This tax shield is calculated as the depreciation amount multiplied by the lessor's marginal tax rate.\\\\n3. PV(Salvage Value): At the end of the lease term, the lessor may recover some value from the asset, known as the salvage value. This is discounted back to its present value.\\\\n4. PV(Purchase Price): The cost of purchasing the asset outright is discounted back to its present value to compare it with the leasing option."
}

