{
  "answer": "To prove that the eventually stationary equilibrium allocation Pareto dominates the autarkic allocation in the odd-even agent model, we proceed as follows:\\nStep 1: Define the autarkic allocation. In the autarkic allocation, each agent consumes their own endowment without engaging in trade. For odd agents, this means consuming $ y_t^o = \\\\[1, 0, 1, 0, \\\\.\\.\\.] $, and for even agents, $ y_t^e = \\\\[0, 1, 0, 1, \\\\.\\.\\.] $. Each agent maximizes their utility function $ \\\\[U_i = \\\\sum_{t=0}^\\\\[infty} \\\\beta^t \\\\ln(c_t^i) $ under these constraints.\\nStep 2: Define the stationary equilibrium allocation. In the stationary equilibrium, agents trade currency to achieve a periodic allocation of consumption goods. This involves odd agents selling currency to even agents during periods when they have excess currency ($ y_t^o = 1 $) and buying it back during periods when they lack currency ($ y_t^o = 0 $). Similarly, even agents sell currency to odd agents during periods when they have excess currency ($ y_t^e = 1 $) and buy it back during periods when they lack currency ($ y_t^e = 0 $).\\nStep 3: Compare utilities. In the autarkic allocation, odd agents consume $ c_t^o = y_t^o $ and even agents consume $ c_t^e = y_t^e $. Their utilities are therefore $ U_o = \\\\[ln(1) + \\\\beta \\\\ln(0) + \\\\ln(1) + \\\\beta \\\\ln(0) + \\\\.\\.\\.] $ and $ U_e = \\\\[ln(0) + \\\\beta \\\\ln(1) + \\\\ln(0) + \\\\beta \\\\ln(1) + \\\\.\\.\\.] $, respectively. Since $ \\\\ln(0) $ is undefined, the autarkic allocation is not feasible.\\nStep 4: Show Pareto dominance. In the stationary equilibrium, odd agents consume $ c_t^o = 1 $ every second period, and even agents consume $ c_t^e = 1 $ every second period. Both agents achieve positive utility in every period, and their total discounted utilities are strictly greater than zero. Thus, the stationary equilibrium allocation Pareto dominates the autarkic allocation because it provides strictly higher utility to both types of agents."
}

