{
  "answer": "To restate Theorem 1.3.2 in terms of indicator functions, we first note that indicator functions map logical statements to binary values (0 or 1). Let $ I_{\\mathbb{A}} $ represent the indicator function for statement $ \\mathbb{A} $. Then:\\n1. Commutativity: $ I_{\\mathbb{A} \\land \\mathbb{B}} = I_{\\mathbb{B} \\land \\mathbb{A}} $ becomes $ I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{B}} = I_{\\mathbb{B}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{A}} $.\\\\\\n2. Associativity: $ I_{(\\mathbb{A} \\land \\mathbb{B}) \\land \\mathbb{C}} = I_{\\mathbb{A} \\land (\\mathbb{B} \\land \\mathbb{C})} $ becomes $ (I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{B}}) \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{C}} = I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot (I_{\\mathbb{B}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{C}}) $.\\\\\\n3. Distributive law: $ I_{(\\mathbb{A} \\lor \\mathbb{B}) \\land \\mathbb{C}} = I_{(\\mathbb{A} \\land \\mathbb{C}) \\lor (\\mathbb{B} \\land \\mathbb{C})} $ becomes $ I_{\\mathbb{A} \\lor \\mathbb{B}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{C}} = (I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{C}}) + (I_{\\mathbb{B}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{C}}) - (I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{B}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{C}}) $.\\\\\\nLet us now prove commutativity using indicator functions. Consider two statements $ \\mathbb{A} $ and $ \\mathbb{B} $ with their respective indicator functions $ I_{\\mathbb{A}} $ and $ I_{\\mathbb{B}} $. By definition, $ I_{\\mathbb{A} \\land \\mathbb{B}} = I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{B}} $. Since multiplication is commutative in real numbers, $ I_{\\mathbb{A}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{B}} = I_{\\mathbb{B}} \\cdot I_{\\mathbb{A}} $. Thus, $ I_{\\mathbb{A} \\land \\mathbb{B}} = I_{\\mathbb{B} \\land \\mathbb{A}} $, proving commutativity."
