  "answer": "Step 1: Recall the definition of deadweight loss. Deadweight loss is the reduction in total surplus (consumer surplus + producer surplus) that occurs when a market is not in equilibrium due to a price floor or ceiling.\\nStep 2: Identify the components of deadweight loss in the labor market. For a minimum wage $W_{min}$ above the equilibrium wage $W^*$, the deadweight loss arises from two sources: (i) the excess supply of labor created by the higher wage, and (ii) the reduced demand for labor at the higher wage.\\nStep 3: Use the elasticities of labor demand ($\\epsilon_D$) and labor supply ($\\\\[epsilon_S$) to quantify the changes in quantity supplied and demanded. The change in labor supplied ($\\\\[Delta]L_S$) and demanded ($\\\\[Delta]L_D$) can be expressed as:\\\\\\\\[Delta]L_S = \\\\[epsilon_S] \\\\cdot \\\\[Delta]W / W^* \\\\\\n\\\\\\[Delta]L_D = -\\\\[epsilon_D] \\\\cdot \\\\[Delta]W / W^* \\\\\\nWhere $\\[Delta]W = W_{min} - W^*$.\\\\\\nStep 4: Calculate the deadweight loss geometrically. The deadweight loss is the area of the triangle formed between the supply and demand curves at the minimum wage. This area can be expressed as:\\\\\\nDeadweight Loss = 0.5 \\\\cdot (\\\\[Delta]L_S + \\\\[Delta]L_D) \\\\cdot \\\\[Delta]W \\\\\\nSubstituting the expressions for $\\[Delta]L_S$ and $\\[Delta]L_D$, we get:\\\\\\nDeadweight Loss = 0.5 \\\\cdot (\\\\[epsilon_S] - \\\\[epsilon_D]) \\\\cdot (\\\\[Delta]W / W^*)^2 \\\\\\nThus, the deadweight loss depends on the difference in elasticities and the size of the wage increase."
