{
  "answer": "To prove that an internal set $ A $ is either finite or uncountable:\\nStep 1: Recall the definition of an internal set. An internal set $ A $ is the equivalence class of a sequence $ X_n $ of subsets of $ \\mathbb{R} $. This means $ A $ inherits properties from the sequence $ X_n $.\\nStep 2: Consider the case where $ X_n $ can be taken as finite for all $ n $. By Definition 11.1.17, such an internal set $ A $ is called star-finite or $ ^\\ast $-finite. Since each $ X_n $ is finite, the equivalence class $ A $ is also finite.\\nStep 3: Now consider the case where $ X_n $ cannot be taken as finite for all $ n $. In this scenario, the internal set $ A $ cannot be countable because if it were countable, it would contradict the structure of $ X_n $ being unable to be finite. Therefore, $ A $ must be uncountable.\\nStep 4: Combining both cases, we conclude that an internal set $ A $ is either finite (if $ X_n $ is finite) or uncountable (if $ X_n $ is not finite)."
}

